    <h4><span class="highlight">OPOWER Beginnings</h4>

    <div class="clearfix">
        
        <div class="span-10">
            <p>Dan Yates and Alex Laskey met the first week of freshman year of college in 1995. By senior year, they had plans to start a business of their own one day. After college, Dan founded an educational software company, Alex ran political campaigns. They stayed in touch. Eleven years later, after selling his first business to Houghton Mifflin, Dan drove from Alaska to Patagonia. In the process he realized the beauty of the world, but also the shocking degradation to the environment caused by humans. He returned to San Francisco, where Alex was working to elect environmentally conscious political candidates, and they decided to focus their entrepreneurial spirit in that arena.</p>        
        </div>

        <div class="span-7 last gallery">
            <a href="css/theme/photos/story-dan.jpg" class="fancybox" title="Dan in South America"><img src="css/theme/photos/story-dan.jpg" /></a>
        </div>
    
    </div>
    
    <p>
        In the Bay Area in 2007, everyone was talking about ways to produce clean energy - solar, wind and other renewables. But Dan and Alex realized that few people were paying attention to the other side of the equation - how to curb wasteful energy usage. While brainstorming ideas on how to help people become more energy efficient they stumbled upon a number - 1.4 billion, the number of utility bills mailed each year. This simple piece of mail, they realized, could be a vehicle to reach millions. But could they motivate them to change their behavior?        
    </p>
    <p>
        They found out about the research of Robert Cialdini, a brilliant behavioral scientist whose research focuses on motivation, influence and other ways to change behavior. They cold called him. And then called him again. They continued calling until Dr. Cialdini agreed to take a sabbatical and join Alex and Dan. The three of them created a prototype utility bill, designed specifically to inform customers and motivate them to behave more efficiently. They enlarged an image of their concept bill, and hit the road.        
    </p>

    <div class="clearfix">
        
        <div class="span-6 gallery">
            <a href="css/theme/photos/story-reports.jpg" class="fancybox" title="Early, early versions of our report"><img src="css/theme/photos/story-reports.jpg" /></a>
        </div>
        <div class="span-11 last">
            <p>
                Poster board in hand, the trio didn't have to go far to find encouragement. Their local utility company was intrigued and, with that support, Dan and Alex began talking to energy officials across the country. They made headway in Texas, where Alex testified at 3 a.m. before the state legislature's energy committee. Soon after that testimony, Texas passed HB-3693, a law requiring Texas utilities to achieve energy efficiency.
            </p>            
        </div>
        <div class="span-17 last">
            <p>
                With that ruling, Dan and Alex had legislative support, they had a product built on cutting-edge behavioral science and they had interest from utility companies. All they needed was a name.        
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

